2026-06-24 23:08:03,458 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Revenue-per-User Comparison: Meta vs. SpaceX AI Segment\n\n### 1. Critical Disclosure Issue (Premise Correction)\n\nThe question\'s premise states that "Meta\'s FY2025 10-K discloses consolidated revenue and average MAUs across its Family of Apps." **This premise is factually incorrect.** Meta\'s FY2025 10-K (filed January 29, 2026) does **not** disclose Monthly Active Users (MAUs) or Monthly Active People (MAP). Meta ceased reporting MAP after Q4 2023 (last disclosed: 3.98B as of December 31, 2023). The FY2025 10-K discloses only:\n- **Daily Active People (DAP):** 3.58 billion (average for December 2025)\n- **Average Revenue Per Person (ARPP):** $57.03 (annual 2025, calculated as FoA revenue ÷ average DAP)\n- **Consolidated revenue:** $200,966 million\n\nBecause no MAU figure exists in Meta\'s FY2025 10-K, I use DAP as the closest available proxy, clearly flagging the methodological limitation. I also cross-check using Meta\'s own ARPP metric.\n\n### 2. Disclosed Figures\n\n| Metric | Meta (FY2025 10-K) | SpaceX AI Segment (S-1) |\n|--------|-------------------|------------------------|\n| Revenue | $200,966M (consolidated) | $3,201M (AI segment) |\n| User base | 3.58B DAP (Dec 2025 avg) — **no MAU disclosed** | 550M combined MAU (Mar 31, 2026) |\n| Revenue composition | ~97%+ advertising | Advertising $1,844M (57.6%) + AI Solutions & Infrastructure $1,357M (42.4%) |\n\nSpaceX AI segment revenue breakdown (FY2025):\n- Advertising: $1,844 million\n- AI Solutions & Infrastructure (X/Grok subscriptions, data licensing, enterprise AI deployments, compute infrastructure): $1,357 million\n\n### 3. Calculations\n\n**Meta implied annual revenue per user (using DAP as proxy):**\n$200,966M ÷ 3,580M = **$56.14 per DAP**\n\n(Alternative using Meta\'s own ARPP: **$57.03 per person** — this is Meta\'s directly disclosed per-person metric, though it is based on DAP, not MAU.)\n\n**SpaceX AI segment revenue per MAU:**\n$3,201M ÷ 550M = **$5.82 per MAU**\n\n**Ratio:**\n- Using DAP proxy: $56.14 ÷ $5.82 = **9.65×**\n- Using ARPP: $57.03 ÷ $5.82 = **9.80×**\n\nMeta generates approximately **9.6–9.8× more revenue per user** than the SpaceX AI segment on this basis.\n\n### 4. What the Gap Implies About Monetization Maturity\n\nA ~9.7× gap implies that the X-plus-Grok platform is at a **substantially earlier stage of monetization maturity** relative to Meta\'s fully mature social advertising business. Meta has spent over a decade building a sophisticated advertising stack — advanced targeting, conversion measurement, auction-based pricing, and a deep advertiser base — that extracts high revenue per user from a global audience. The X-plus-Grok platform, by contrast, is in early-stage monetization: a majority of its revenue still comes from advertising on X, but a large minority (42.4%) comes from subscriptions, data licensing, and enterprise AI/compute — streams that are not yet scaled and, in the case of enterprise AI, are not consumer-advertising in nature at all. The gap suggests meaningful headroom for monetization improvement if the platform can mature its advertising business toward Meta-like efficiency. However, as detailed below, the ratio overstates the "efficiency gap" due to structural comparability problems.\n\n### 5. Two Structural Reasons the Ratio Cannot Be Interpreted as a Straightforward Monetization Efficiency Comparison\n\n#### Reason 1 — Revenue Mix Mismatch (Numerator Problem)\n\nThe SpaceX AI segment\'s $3,201M numerator is **not a pure consumer-advertising revenue figure**. It blends:\n- $1,844M in X advertising (directly tied to consumer MAUs), and\n- $1,357M in "AI Solutions & Infrastructure," which includes X/Grok consumer subscriptions, data licensing, **enterprise AI deployments (Grok Business/Enterprise)**, and **compute infrastructure** revenue.\n\nThe enterprise AI and compute infrastructure components are B2B revenue streams monetized through license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing — they are **not monetized through the 550M consumer MAUs** in the denominator. This creates a **numerator-denominator mismatch**: the denominator captures consumer platform users, but the numerator includes revenue from buyers (enterprises) who are not in the MAU count. Meta\'s revenue, by contrast, is overwhelmingly advertising (~97%+) tied directly to its consumer user base, so its numerator and denominator are economically aligned. Comparing a blended B2C+B2B revenue figure against a consumer-only user base to Meta\'s advertising-only revenue against a consumer-only user base is not an apples-to-apples efficiency comparison.\n\n#### Reason 2 — Disclosure Design Incompatibility (Denominator Problem)\n\nMeta\'s FY2025 10-K **does not disclose MAUs at all**. The only user-engagement metric disclosed is DAP (Daily Active People), a **daily** metric, while SpaceX\'s 550M figure is a **monthly** metric (MAU). This introduces multiple incompatibilities:\n\n- **Metric frequency mismatch:** DAP (daily) ≠ MAU (monthly). A daily active count is structurally lower than a monthly active count for the same platform, so dividing annual revenue by DAP produces a higher per-user figure than dividing by MAU would. Using DAP as a proxy for MAU systematically inflates Meta\'s apparent revenue-per-user relative to a true MAU-based calculation.\n- **Temporal mismatch:** SpaceX\'s 550M MAU is a **point-in-time figure as of March 31, 2026** — after the FY2025 revenue period — and has grown from 520M at December 31, 2025. Using the higher March 2026 user count against FY2025 revenue understates SpaceX\'s per-user revenue relative to the average user base during 2025. Meta\'s DAP is an average for December 2025, a different measurement convention.\n- **Definitional scope mismatch:** SpaceX\'s MAU counts only **registered users** who interacted with Grok or X via web/mobile in the prior 30 days. Meta\'s DAP counts **unique people** (including unregistered, where applicable) across Facebook, Instagram, Messenger, and WhatsApp. The population definitions are not equivalent.\n\nBecause Meta does not disclose a monthly user metric, no directly comparable MAU denominator exists, and the DAP proxy introduces a frequency, temporal, and definitional distortion. The resulting ratio is therefore a rough directional indicator, not a clean monetization-efficiency benchmark.\n\n### Summary\n\n| | Meta (FY2025) | SpaceX AI Segment (FY2025) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Revenue | $200,966M | $3,201M |\n| User metric | 3.58B DAP (no MAU disclosed) | 550M MAU (Mar 31, 2026) |\n| Revenue per user | ~$56.14 (DAP proxy) / $57.03 (ARPP) | $5.82 per MAU |\n| **Ratio** | **~9.65×–9.80×** | **1.0×** |\n\nThe ~9.7× gap signals that X-plus-Grok is far less monetization-mature than Meta\'s advertising business, but the ratio is not a clean efficiency comparison because (1) SpaceX\'s AI segment revenue includes non-consumer B2B streams (enterprise AI, compute, data licensing) not tied to the MAU denominator, and (2) Meta does not disclose MAUs, forcing use of a daily metric (DAP) as a proxy, which introduces frequency, temporal, and definitional incompatibilities with SpaceX\'s monthly MAU figure.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1326801/000162828026003942/meta-20251231.htm",\n      "name": "Meta Platforms, Inc. Form 10-K for fiscal year ended December 31, 2025 (filed January 29, 2026)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "Space Exploration Technologies Corp. (SpaceX) Form S-1 (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
